&lt;p style=&quot;user-select: auto;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center; user-select: auto;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; style=&quot;user-select: auto;&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong style=&quot;user-select: auto;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; font-size: 21px; user-select: auto;&quot;&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;user-select: auto;&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;user-select: auto;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;user-select: auto;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong style=&quot;user-select: auto;&quot;&gt;Anushilan Samiti &lt;/strong&gt;was an Indian fitness club, which was also used as a&amp;nbsp;hidden&amp;nbsp;society for anti-British Indian revolutionaries.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;user-select: auto;&quot;&gt;Anushilan Samiti was led by the nationalists &lt;strong style=&quot;user-select: auto;&quot;&gt;Aurobindo Ghosh&lt;/strong&gt; and his brother &lt;strong style=&quot;user-select: auto;&quot;&gt;Barindra Ghosh&lt;/strong&gt;, influenced by philosophies like Italian Nationalism, and the&lt;strong style=&quot;user-select: auto;&quot;&gt; Pan-Asianism of Kakuzo Okakura.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;user-select: auto;&quot;&gt;The organization moved&amp;nbsp;from its philosophy of violence in the &lt;strong style=&quot;user-select: auto;&quot;&gt;1920s&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;because of&amp;nbsp;the influence of the Indian National Congress and&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong style=&quot;user-select: auto;&quot;&gt;Mahatma Gandhi&amp;#39;s&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong style=&quot;user-select: auto;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;non-violent movement.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;user-select: auto;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;A&lt;strong style=&quot;user-select: auto;&quot;&gt; number of Congress leaders from Bengal&lt;/strong&gt;, especially &lt;strong style=&quot;user-select: auto;&quot;&gt;Subhash Chandra Bose, &lt;/strong&gt;were accused by the &lt;strong style=&quot;user-select: auto;&quot;&gt;British Government &lt;/strong&gt;because of having connectivity&amp;nbsp;with the organization during that&amp;nbsp;time.&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;user-select: auto;&quot;&gt;So we conclude that the correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder; user-select: auto;&quot;&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;user-select: auto;&quot;&gt;Rajendra Lahiri.&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;user-select: auto;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center; user-select: auto;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; style=&quot;user-select: auto;&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong style=&quot;user-select: auto;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; font-size: 21px; user-select: auto;&quot;&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;user-select: auto;&quot;&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;user-select: auto;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;user-select: auto;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong style=&quot;user-select: auto;&quot;&gt;Barindra Kumar Ghosh&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;popularly was an Indian-birth revolutionary and journalist.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;user-select: auto;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong style=&quot;user-select: auto;&quot;&gt;Barindra Ghosh&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;was one of the founding members of &lt;strong style=&quot;user-select: auto;&quot;&gt;Jugantar Bengali&lt;/strong&gt; Weekly, a revolutionary outfit in Bengal.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;user-select: auto;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong style=&quot;user-select: auto;&quot;&gt;Bhupendra Nath Datta&lt;/strong&gt; was an Indian&amp;nbsp;revolutionary and later a noted sociologist and anthropologist.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;user-select: auto;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong style=&quot;user-select: auto;&quot;&gt;Jatindra Nath Banerjee &lt;/strong&gt;was one of two great Indian-birth&amp;nbsp;nationalists and freedom fighters &amp;ndash; along with &lt;strong style=&quot;user-select: auto;&quot;&gt;Aurobindo Ghosh&lt;/strong&gt;,&amp;nbsp;who dramatically rose to prominence between &lt;strong style=&quot;user-select: auto;&quot;&gt;1871 and 1910&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;Polaj.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The term used to describe the land which had been continuously cultivated in the &lt;strong&gt;Zabti system&lt;/strong&gt; during the Mughal Empire is &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;Polaj&amp;quot;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The Zabti system was a&lt;strong&gt; land revenue system&lt;/strong&gt; introduced by &lt;strong&gt;Akbar&lt;/strong&gt; in the &lt;strong&gt;16th century,&lt;/strong&gt; which aimed to ensure a&lt;strong&gt; regular flow of revenue&lt;/strong&gt; to the state and &lt;strong&gt;prevent exploitation&lt;/strong&gt; of peasants by officials.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;Banjar&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; refers to the&lt;strong&gt; uncultivated or fallow land.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;Parauti&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; refers to the land which was cultivated but &lt;strong&gt;left uncultivated f&lt;/strong&gt;or a year or more.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;Chachar&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; refers to the land which was cultivated but produced &lt;strong&gt;no crop&lt;/strong&gt; due to natural calamities.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The Zabti system was based on an &lt;strong&gt;assessment of the yield of the land&lt;/strong&gt; and fixed rates of revenue were charged accordingly.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The system was efficient in ensuring a regular flow of revenue to the state, but it also led to the &lt;strong&gt;exploitation of peasants&lt;/strong&gt; who were forced to pay fixed rates even if their crops failed due to natural calamities.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The Zabti system was later replaced by the&lt;strong&gt; Ryotwari system&lt;/strong&gt; in British India, which gave individual cultivators the right to own and cultivate land and pay revenue directly to the state.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;u&gt;Explanation:&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Metals reaction with dilute Acid&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Metals react with dilute acid to form metal salt and release hydrogen gas.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The hydrogen gas burns with a pop sound and this signifies the presence of hydrogen gas.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;All metals do not react with dilute acid to release hydrogen.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The metals above hydrogen in the reactivity series do that and the &lt;strong&gt;metal below in the reactivity series do not release hydrogen (no reaction).&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;​&lt;/strong&gt;Metal + dil. Acid&amp;nbsp;&amp;rarr;&amp;nbsp;Metal salt + Hydrogen Gas&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;How does the metal reactivity series work? + Example&quot; src=&quot;https://storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/21/01/F4_Utkarsha_8-1-2021_Swati_D5.png&quot; style=&quot;height: 227px; width: 400px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Among the given metals, only copper is below hydrogen.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;So, the correct option is copper.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Copper reacts with sulphuric acid on heating but do not react with dilute hydrochloric acid.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Western Ghats&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;The Western Ghats are also known as&amp;nbsp;Sahyadri.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The Western ghats:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;The western ghat&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is the mountain range parallel to the western coast of the Indian peninsula.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The total length of the western ghat is around&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;1600 km.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The western ghat region is spread from&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Tapti to Kanyakumari.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It passes through the Indian states of Tamil Nadu, Kerala, Karnataka, Goa, Maharashtra, and Gujarat.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Anamudi&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is the highest peak of the western ghat.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;All important rivers of Peninsular India originate from the western ghat.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The major hill stations of the western ghat are Amboli ghat, Matheran,&amp;nbsp;Mahabaleshwar,&amp;nbsp;Panchgani,&amp;nbsp;Kudremukh.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Aravalli Range&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is a mountain range in&amp;nbsp;&lt;span class=&quot;mw-redirect&quot; style=&quot;background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;&quot; title=&quot;Northwestern India&quot;&gt;Northwestern India&lt;/span&gt;, the length of the range is&amp;nbsp;approximately &lt;strong&gt;692&amp;nbsp;km&amp;nbsp;in a south-west direction.&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Aravalli range is starting from&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Delhi&lt;/span&gt;, passing through southern&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;&quot; title=&quot;Haryana&quot;&gt;Haryana&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;and&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Rajasthan&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;,&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;and ending in&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;background-image: none; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;&quot; title=&quot;Gujarat&quot;&gt;Gujarat&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The literal meaning of Aravalli Range is &amp;lsquo;line of peaks&amp;rsquo;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Eastern Ghats:&lt;/span&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;A discontinuous range of mountains along India&amp;#39;s eastern coast runs parallel to the Bay of Bengal.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;They are eroded and cut through by the four major rivers of peninsular India, Godavari, Mahanadi, Krishna and Kaveri.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Some of the important ranges include the&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;Shevaroy hills, Javadi hills, the Palconda range, the Nallamala hills, the Mahendragiri hills,&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;etc.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Vindhya Range&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;oldest mountain range&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;of&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Madhya Pradesh&lt;/span&gt;.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Vindhya Range is the&amp;nbsp;broken range of hills forming the southern escarpment of the central upland of India.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;From Gujarat state on the west, it extends about 1,086 km&amp;nbsp;across Madhya Pradesh state to adjoining on the Ganga&amp;nbsp;River valley near Varanasi, Uttar Pradesh.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Kaimur&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;hills&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;are the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;easternmost&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;hill of the Vindhya Range.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Kakrabardi&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;hills&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;are the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;westernmost&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;hill of the Vindhya Range.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

